## Primary dependency: vercel-labs/agent-browser

- **Project:** https://github.com/vercel-labs/agent-browser
- **License:** Apache License 2.0
- **Maintainer:** Vercel Labs and contributors
- **Role in silent-browser-use:** the entire browser-automation engine.

`silent-browser-use` does **not** vendor, fork, or modify any source code from
`agent-browser`. We invoke the upstream CLI binary as a subprocess (typically
`agent-browser connect --ws ws://127.0.0.1:9222/...`) and stream JSON events
back to Python. When `agent-browser` releases a new version, users upgrade the
binary independently and `silent-browser-use` follows automatically — no
version pinning, no patch set to maintain.

If `agent-browser`'s license terms ever conflict with this notice, the upstream
license governs. See the upstream repository for the full text of the Apache
License 2.0 and any `NOTICE` it ships.

---

## Design inspiration: browser-use / browser-harness

- **Project:** https://github.com/browser-use/browser-use
- **License:** MIT
- **Maintainer:** browser-use organisation and contributors
- **Role in silent-browser-use:** design inspiration only.

The "persistent agent window" pattern — one long-lived browser window per user,
many short-lived sessions reusing it, a snapshot-first ergonomics with ARIA
refs — is borrowed directly from `browser-use` / `browser-harness`. Our Python
implementation is written from scratch and does not copy upstream code; the
shape of the API and the user-facing UX, however, owe a clear debt to that
project.

If you need a more feature-complete persistent browser harness with a richer
ecosystem, go check out `browser-use` directly — it is excellent.

---

## Other prior art we learned from

- **[Playwright](https://playwright.dev)** (Apache 2.0, Microsoft and contributors) — helper signatures (`fill`, `click`, `wait_for`) intentionally rhyme with Playwright's, so users coming from Playwright can guess our API correctly on the first try.
- **[Puppeteer](https://pptr.dev)** (Apache 2.0, Google and contributors) — the spiritual ancestor of CDP-driven Chrome automation.
- **[rebrowser-patches](https://github.com/rebrowser/rebrowser-patches)** — a reminder that stealth/anti-detection is a *separate* concern that we deliberately do not address; users needing it should compose those patches themselves.

